### 1. Brief Summary of the Facts  
The case involves a dispute over the validity of two wills executed by Nina Wang, the late chairwoman of the Chinachem Group (a private conglomerate valued at approximately $100 billion). The **2002 will** left her entire estate to the Chinachem Charitable Foundation (the plaintiff), a charity co-founded by her and her late husband, Teddy Wang. The **2006 will** (allegedly signed by Nina Wang on 16 October 2006) named the first defendant, Chan Chun Chuen—a feng shui master and long-term secret lover of Nina Wang—as the beneficiary. The plaintiff sought to probate the 2002 will and invalidate the 2006 will, which the first defendant claimed was genuine.  

The judge (Lam J) found the 2006 will to be a **forgery**, based on:  
- **Attending witnesses’ testimony**: Solicitor Mr. Winfield Wong and Mr. Ng Shung Mo (a Chinachem employee) testified that the document they witnessed on 16 October 2006 was a *partial will* (bequeathing $10 million to a Mr. Chan), not the 2006 will. The 2006 will lacked this bequest and contained other discrepancies.  
- **Handwriting analysis**: Experts concluded Nina Wang’s signature on the 2006 will was a *highly skilled simulation*, and Mr. Wong’s signature was also forged. The judge emphasized the *accumulation of rare features* in the signatures as critical evidence of forgery.  
- **Contextual evidence**: Nina Wang maintained a lifelong commitment to the charitable foundation, despite her relationship with Chan (which was kept secret). Large payments to Chan (e.g., $688 million in 2005–2007) were tied to feng shui rituals (e.g., hole-digging to locate her missing husband, later to combat her cancer), but she never altered her 2002 will. The judge rejected the first defendant’s claim that the 2002 will was a "public image enhancement exercise."  

The judge ordered the plaintiff to have costs on an indemnity basis, reflecting the first defendant’s *gross abuse of court process* in presenting a forged will.  

